node.text:
Your 2030 lifestyle will be determined by your 2021 decisions.

The most important thing you can do to make sure your 2030 lifestyle will be exactly, if not better, than what you want is to be BUILDING:

Building Your Business. Your Body. Your health. Your self-esteem. Your bank account. 

The problem is... By 2030 most people reading this WILL NOT build anything significant for
themselves and their families.

Why? 

Because they lack the tools, education, and experience. And most importantly... They lack Guidance.

Our current education system doesn't teach us how to build the future we really want. 

We learn different topics that will help us have great 9-5 or different careers... That in fact won't help us build the future we REALLY want.

That's why today I highly recommend you to follow some of the best mentors on Instagram.

The key to learning how to build your best future is by learning from the people who have already done it & teach you how you can do it too. 

Their daily Instagram posts will help you a lot. 
Here they are:

1) @tanner.chidester 

2) @kingketo

3) @derekmoneyberg

4) @thechrisnaugle

5) @shawnsharma

6) @pouyahaidari

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Business & Entrepreneur on July 19, 2021 tagging @chitabnb. May be a Twitter screenshot of text that says 'Chi Ta @itschitabnb Biggest financial mistakes early in my journey. (A thread)'.

Photo by Business & Entrepreneur on July 19, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Chi Ta @itschitabnb 1. Not investing sooner Investing $400 per month starting at 20 will be $1,867,995 at 65 Investing $400 per month starting at 35 will be $547,784 at 65 Assuming 8% return The sooner you start investing the sooner you can start reaping the benefits of compound interest.'.

Photo by Business & Entrepreneur on July 19, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Chi Ta @itschitabnb 2. Not having a budget Create a budget and stick to it. You should know exactly where every dollar is going. If you just leave it sitting around you'll be more likely to spend it.'.

Photo by Business & Entrepreneur on July 19, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Chi Ta @itschitabnb 3. Buying liabilities instead of assets Buy things that pay you money, not take your money. While buying materialistic things might be fun short term, it has no long term value. Acquire assets first, then have your assets pay for your liabilities.'.

Photo by Business & Entrepreneur on July 19, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Chi Ta @itschitabnb 4. Having a short term mindset Whatever you want to do in life you need to think long term and be patient, whether that's investing, building a business, learning a skill. You have to be willing to put in the work without expecting immediate results.'.

Photo by Business & Entrepreneur on July 19, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Chi Ta @itschitabnb 5. Buying things to impress others The truth is, no one cares about the things you own. Spend your money wisely, buy things that will give you freedom, not status.'.

Photo by Business & Entrepreneur on July 19, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Chi Ta @itschitabnb 6. Thinking all debt is bad Not all debt is bad, you can leverage credit to acquire assets that increase in value or provide you great cash flow every month. Only borrow money to make more money or don't borrow it at all.'.

Photo shared by Business & Entrepreneur on July 19, 2021 tagging @chitabnb. May be a Twitter screenshot of text that says 'Chi Ta @itschitabnb this helpful. Hopefully you found If you'd you'd like to see more content abon what learned as an entrepreneur and from building my short term rental business to $2.4M in 9 months, drop me a follow.'.
